 in plane polar coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $(r,\varphi)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Laplacian in these coordinates is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\nabla^{2}=\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial r^{2}}+\frac{1}{r}\frac{\partial}{\partial r}+\frac{1}{r^{2}}\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial\varphi^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The potential is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V(r)=\frac{1}{2}kr^{2}=\frac{1}{2}\mu\omega^{2}r^{2}
\]

\end_inset

Where 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=(k/\mu)^{1/2}$
\end_inset

.
 The Hamiltonian is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
H & = & -\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2\mu}\nabla^{2}+V(r)=-\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2\mu}\nabla^{2}+\frac{1}{2}\mu\omega^{2}r^{2}\\
 & = & -\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2\mu}\Bigg[\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial r^{2}}+\frac{1}{r}\frac{\partial}{\partial r}+\frac{1}{r^{2}}\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial\varphi^{2}}\Bigg]+\frac{1}{2}\mu\omega^{2}r^{2}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

So the Schrödinger equation for the two dimensional isotropic oscillator
 in these coordinates is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Bigg(-\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2\mu}\Bigg[\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial r^{2}}+\frac{1}{r}\frac{\partial}{\partial r}+\frac{1}{r^{2}}\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial\varphi^{2}}\Bigg]+\frac{1}{2}\mu\omega^{2}r^{2}\Bigg)\psi(r,\varphi)=E\psi(r,\varphi)
\]

\end_inset

According to the book the solution to this is separable so
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi(r,\varphi)=R_{El}(r)\Phi(\varphi)
\]

\end_inset

The 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi(\varphi)$
\end_inset

 function is the same as the one from the spherical harmonic function 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{lm}(\theta,\varphi)=\Theta_{lm}(\theta)\Phi_{m}(\phi)$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Phi(\varphi)=\Phi_{m}(\varphi)=e^{im\varphi}
\]

\end_inset

with some normalization constant.
 So the solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(r,\varphi)$
\end_inset

 has the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi_{lm}=R_{El}(r)e^{im\varphi}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The radial part 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{El}$
\end_inset

